# System Design — Orakara

## Overview

Orakara is a structured B2B procurement platform. Its core technical challenge is not data storage or retrieval — it is *process integrity*: ensuring that two parties with misaligned incentives move through a multi-stage negotiation in a way that is fair, auditable, and resistant to manipulation.

Every architectural decision flows from that requirement.

---

## Decision 1 — Deterministic State Machine over Event-Driven Architecture

### What we chose

The entire negotiation lifecycle is encoded as an explicit, linear state machine with a single orchestrator (`negotiationOrchestrator.ts`) controlling all transitions. Stage progression is synchronous. No transition fires unless all preconditions are validated first.

```
PENDING → RESPONDED → NEGOTIATING_SPECS → [SAMPLE_REQUESTED] → NEGOTIATING_PRICE → NEGOTIATING_CONTRACT → DEAL_CREATED
```

Each arrow is a function call. Each function call either succeeds completely or throws and rolls back. There are no partial states.

### Why not event-driven

An event-driven architecture would let subsystems react to domain events independently — a `PriceAgreed` event could trigger the contract stage to initialise, a `TimerExpired` event could fire failure logic automatically, and so on.

The problem is that our stages are not independent. The price stage cannot begin until the spec stage has reached full agreement. The contract stage cannot proceed until price, payment mode, quantity, lead time, and — if PLATFORM_ESCROW — tranche structure are all individually agreed. If those validations are spread across event handlers, the invariants become distributed, and the system can reach incoherent states when handlers execute out of order, retry after partial success, or fail silently.

A practical example: if `PriceAgreed` fires before tranche negotiation completes (because tranches are negotiated in parallel in an event-driven model), the contract stage could initialise with an incomplete payment structure. In the deterministic model, `isPricePaymentAgreed()` checks all four dimensions in a single synchronous gate before any transition is allowed. It is structurally impossible to enter the contract stage with an incomplete price agreement.

### The debugging argument

When a deal enters a bad state in production, the error trace leads to a single function call in `negotiationOrchestrator.ts`. The precondition that failed is explicit. No reasoning about which event fired when, which handler consumed it, or whether the message queue delivered it exactly once.

In an event-driven model, debugging a state inconsistency requires reconstructing a causal chain from async event logs. In a deterministic model, it requires reading one stack trace.

### The cognitive load argument

This matters beyond engineering. One of the core product goals is to reduce the cognitive load on negotiating parties so they can make better-quality decisions — specifically, to help them converge toward the [Kaldor-Hicks efficient outcome](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kaldor%E2%80%93Hicks_efficiency) where one exists.

A negotiation platform that is itself unpredictable undermines this goal. If users encounter a stage transition that happens at an unexpected moment, or a turn that flips when they did not expect it, they lose confidence in the system and begin second-guessing the process rather than the deal terms. The deterministic model ensures that upon repeated use, the sequence becomes second nature — users build accurate mental models of the system, and those mental models hold under all conditions.

