## Decision 3 — Next.js API Routes as the Backend Layer

### What we chose

All backend logic lives inside Next.js API routes (`src/app/api/`), deployed to Vercel. There is no separate backend service.

### Why

At current scale, the operational overhead of maintaining a separate API service (separate deployment, separate CI/CD, cross-origin credential handling, inter-service latency) is not justified. Next.js API routes give us:

- Co-located frontend and backend deployment
- Shared TypeScript types across the stack (Zod schemas defined once, used for both API validation and client-side form validation)
- Vercel Cron for the three scheduled jobs (timer expiry every 5 minutes, holiday pause/resume daily, RFQ expiry every 15 minutes) with no additional infrastructure

The separation boundary is logical, not physical: `src/lib/` contains all business logic (orchestrator, failure tracking, cron processors, export utilities) and is never imported by frontend components. API routes are thin handlers that validate input, call `src/lib/` functions, and return responses. This means a future migration to a separate API service requires moving `src/lib/` and the route handlers — the business logic itself does not need to change.

---

## Schema Design Philosophy

The schema is deliberately denormalised in places where query performance at read time matters more than write-time normalisation purity. The `Inquiry` model, for instance, carries turn tracking fields (`specNegotiationTurn`, `priceNegotiationTurn`) directly rather than resolving them via a join. This is intentional: turn validation runs on every state-mutating API call, and the turn fields are needed immediately. Eliminating the join on the hot path is worth the denormalisation cost.

Audit and research data are stored in dedicated models (`AuditLog`, `NegotiationFailure`, `BehavioralEvent`) that are append-only by design. No audit record is ever updated or deleted in application code. This provides an immutable event log independent of the mutable operational state.

---

## Cron Architecture

Three Vercel Cron jobs run the time-sensitive background processes:

| Job | Schedule | What it does |
|---|---|---|
| `/api/cron/timers` | Every 5 min | Expires timers, records failures, sends timer warnings |
| `/api/cron/holidays` | Daily at 18:00 | Pauses / resumes all active timers per country based on holiday calendar | (in fluz, may be discarded)
| `/api/cron/rfq-expiry` | Every 15 min | Marks stale RFQs as expired |

All three converge in `src/lib/cron/index.ts → runAllCronJobs()`. Each job writes an `AuditLog` record on completion. Timer expiry is idempotent — re-running on an already-expired timer is a no-op.
